76561198067479076,Recommended,280040,10537304,"Posted: 19 June, 2014",all,Cheeseburger Fingers,"Alright, after many more hours with this game I am amending my previous review.I previously said that the equipment you get makes such a small difference it's unnoticable.  I take that back.  The equipment that raises your attack speed and your overall speed definitely make a noticable difference.  The equipment I have a problem with is the spiked set.  Raising your damage by 1 really doesn't do anything to help you, and it's much more worthwhile to wear, say, the Ranger set to increase your mobility or the lead set to increase your HP.  Spiked set should add more offense.I also said that the never-changing layout was dull.  I fully retract that comment.  The more I play the game, the more I'm thankful that the layout (i.e., blueprints always on the same floor, pentagram always on the same floor, townsperson always on the same floor) stays the same, so I know what I should be looking for each floor.Now that I'm at the point where I'm nearing the crypt, my only real problem other than the spiked set is the slow down.  In the sewers, the slowdown (which I believe is caused by the poison traps in the walls) makes things very difficult, borderline unplayable.  After fighting the boss of the sewers five times in a row and each time having my run end unfortunately with a massive slowdown, it begins to get frustrating.Other than that, this game has grown on me quite a bit, I find it a blast, and I would recommend it to anyone.  Hopefully there are tweaks to come."
,Recommended,280040,11105778,"Posted: 6 July, 2014",all,Explogan,"I am a massive fan of Binding of Issac and have played a lot of rogue-likes since then which have all tried to emulate the same style of gameplay but either end up feeling too similar or too different to really scratch that itch.A Wizard's Lizard is a perfect mash-up of BOI and Rogue Legacy, while bringing some of it's own very creative ideas to the table. The Rogue Legacy trend of persistent improvement has often fallen into the trap of making your character too powerful or over-ruling the skill aspect. With A Wizard's Lizard it feels like the equipment that you unlock and the gold that you build up is all about building the character you'd like to play as, while being very balanced. If you want a lot of offense, you'll need to sacrifice attack rate and you won't have much money left over to increase your other stats. It also saves the frustration that can occur with random generation and not getting the items that you most enjoy playing with.Highly recommend AWL, it has gamepad, keyboard and Mouse & keyboard support - the latter has surprised me as my favourite, but having an aiming reticle has gotten me out of the BOI trap of only shooting in 4 directions. There's also a really interesting second life mechanic which is used in some creative ways - yet to figure it out!Love it, I know I'll sink a lot of time into it."
