76561197995158485,Not Recommended,280040,15743660,"Posted: 8 May, 2015",all,Searanox,"A Wizard’s Lizard is a rogue-like that resembles Link to the Past in its design. In it you play as Raga, a wizard’s pet lizard. Your master tries to cheat death and Death comes to take him personally. It’s up to you to go and rescue him.The town of Amberfall is all but deserted when you start, but you can find villagers as you traverse the dungeons in search of your master. Each villager you find will increase your starting gold by five hundred. So, if you save ten people, you’ll start each run with 5000 gold to spend. You also find blueprints, which eventually make every item in the game accessible. With enough patience and enough townsfolk rescued, you can unlock almost every item in the game and have enough money to outfit yourself before you even step into the dungeon itself.Like most rogue-likes, A Wizard’s Lizard is randomly-generated in almost every aspect. Random dungeon layouts with random monsters with random loot and random rewards. All of which goes down the tubes when you die. There’s no reward for skill or progress beyond saving townsfolk and recovering blueprints so you have access to more items. There are shortcuts, which can be unlocked by destroying giant killer crystals, multiple times. But other than that, it’s just running the same random rooms over, and over, and over again. I’m just not impressed.There are nine levels in all, spanning a Graveyard, a Sewer, and a Crypt. There are others but darn if I couldn’t find them but once in a blue moon. I only ever got as far as the first area of the crypt. The random nature of the game along with the dwindling chance for health items as you go makes for a nearly impossible path from start to finish. The best you can hope to do is just open all the short cuts so that you start out further along than normal. This game suffers from a lot of strange issues. Let me count them out:-Occasionally the controls will lock up and have you running upward forever.-The aiming retical here is NOT on top of everything like it should be, you can lose it in a crowd.-There are a rather large number of enemies that can’t be harmed when they’re sitting still.-There are weapons in the game that can kill you if used improperly.-There are zero enemies in the game that can be killed in one hit, even with top weapons and armor.-The game keeps track of all the enemies you’ve killed and items found when this could’ve just been done on a menu screen to track progress. Instead it’s a weird museum-statue area.The unique mechanic that comes with this game is dying. When Raga dies he becomes a ghost and suddenly you must fight both the living and the dead enemies in every room. Handfuls of living enemies turn into spirits, skeletons, and flaming skulls. So, if you wander into a room and you’re already dead chances are you’ll have to kill most everything twice. This isn’t fun, it’s tedious.Thankfully there are rare resurrection circles. I had to google what they did since the game doesn’t tell you— but if you stand in one while in ghost form you’ll be brought back to life with some of your health. But, if you die as a ghost the game’s over. You lose all your items, money, and progress. Like nothing mattered.I can go ahead and say I couldn’t beat this game, it’s just not for me. I made it seven levels in and it wasn’t from lack of trying. I didn’t get a single one of the game’s difficult achievements. I didn’t save the wizard, and I never even made it to the final boss. The increasing difficulty and the decreasing of health-items makes the game harder than it should be. Combine this with bad weapon-balancing, mobile obstacles, and the random nature of the beast and you’ve got a recipe for frustration more than you do for fun. Avoid this one."
