,Not Recommended,280040,19453649,"Posted: 2 December, 2015",all,Darkwell,"This is not a good rogue-like. Or a good rogue-like-like.A rogue-like, in my mind, is defined by high - but not unfair - difficulty. As you progress through a rogue-like, you should become skilled in avoiding enemies, avoiding damage. A rogue-like should force you to become skilled, and you should enjoy yourself by conquering challenges as your skill increases.A Wizard's Lizard has gotten that wrong.You never need to become more skilled. You don't need to learn anything, in fact. I beat the game on my second attempt. Took less than two hours. Well, maybe the additional characters you unlock change things up?No.Unlockable characters are IDENTICAL to the base class; all that changes is starting equipment, which you'll trash within minutes of playing anyway.Well, what else could keep you playing? Increased difficulty? Doesn't exist. Speedruns? Yawn. Achievements? Nothing challenging. Seriously. The achievements for WizLiz are nearly all achievable without significant changes in play or thought.It's just...not a fun game.Don't buy it."
